We can either build a thinner cylinder and extrude faces out or we can build a thicker cylinder and extrude faces in/boolean shapes out. Both are okay.Â 

In this case, we choose the first route.Â 

The first hard part is to determine the number of subdivisions.Â 

We know we need three lines for sure, one for center and two for the side, then we need two more in between so we have more control of the shape.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

We know the two lines on the side are shared. So one shape would need 3 + 2*0.5 = 4 lines. And there are 8 of these shapes and 8 parts of the area in between. So we need 4 * (8 + 8) = 64 subdivisions on the cylinder.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Then, we scale the vertices and extrude faces, we get the primary shape.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

We add one horizontal edge across the mesh, then we have the area defined for the extrude out.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

In order to move two vertices along the surface, we first need to check keep spacing on transform tool setting (marking menu: w + left click), then select both vertices, press d and v to snap the pivot to the outside vertice, then press c and middle mouse the edge to move them along the surface.Â
